tures were a purely&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Visual_arts\">visual art</a>, but these innovative&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Silent_film\">silent films</a>&nbsp;had gained a hold on the public imagination. Rather than leave audiences with only the noise of the projector as an accompaniment, theater owners hired a&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Piano\">pianist</a>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Organ_(music)\">organist</a>&nbsp;or, in large urban theaters, a full&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orchestra\">orchestra</a>&nbsp;to play music that fit the mood of the film at any given moment. By the early 1920s, most films came with a prepared list of sheet music to be used for this purpose, and complete&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Film_score\">film scores</a>&nbsp;were composed for major productions.</p>', '1617188693-services_4.jpg', '', '', '', 1, '2021-03-24 09:05:50', NULL),
