shocks.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3>Before celluloid</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stroboscopic_effect\">stroboscopic</a>&nbsp;animation principle was introduced in 1833 with the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phenakistiscope\">ph&eacute;nakisticope</a>&nbsp;and also applied in the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zoetrope\">zoetrope</a>&nbsp;since 1866, the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flip_book\">flip book</a>&nbsp;since 1868, and the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Praxinoscope\">praxinoscope</a>&nbsp;since 1877, before it became the basic principle for cinematography.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Experiments with early phenakisticope-based animation projectors were made at least as early as 1843.&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jules_Duboscq\">Jules Duboscq</a>&nbsp;marketed ph&eacute;nakisticope projection systems in France between 1853 and the 1890s.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Photography\">Photography</a>&nbsp;was introduced in 1839, but at first&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Photographic_emulsion\">photographic emulsions</a>&nbsp;needed such long&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exposure_(photography)\">exposures</a>&nbsp;that the recording of moving subjects seemed impossible. At least as early as 1844, photographic series of subjects posed in different positions have been created to either suggest a motion sequence or to document a range of different viewing angles. The advent of stereoscopic photography, with early experiments in the 1840s and commercial success since the early 1850s, raised interest in completing the photographic medium with the addition of means to capture colour and motion. In 1849,&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joseph_Plateau\">Joseph Plateau</a>&nbsp;published about the idea to combine his invention of the ph&eacute;nakisticope with the stereoscope, as suggested to him by stereoscope